>> VARIANCE  
@quoted
mean of sum of squares of displacement form the mean (MU).

`∑ (X - µ)^2 - (n) =  (∑ X^2)/n - µ^2`

Combined Variance for datasets 1 and 2:

`(∑ X1^2) + (∑ X2^2) / (n1 + n2) - µ^2`

in other words,

`(∑ X1^2) + (∑ X2^2) / total new frequency - µ^2`

    >> DEVIATION 

Standard deviation is the *square root of variance*, in fact variance is
denoted by *σ^2*, and standard deviation is *σ*.

'NOTE' to get Standard Deviation we need: mean and variance.

Combined standard deviation is the `sqrt(combined variance)`.

    POISSON'S DISTRIBUTION

It models events which are randomly distributed in time or space, with
a mean number of occurrences in a given time interval.

`` It takes only 1 parameter - the mean denoted by lambda *λ*.

When using the Poisson's distribution, we assume that the random variable
we are investigating does follow this distribution.'

An important property of the Poisson Distribution is the fact that 
*the mean (lambda) is always equal to variance*.

    `P(X=3) = (e^(-λ) \* λ^x) / x!`

Because the formula requires us to take something to the power of x,
computationally this will be very demanding so once out variable goes over
10 - 15 we should really use an approximation to the natural
distribution. (exponential growth)

To calculate Poisson, we use tables with pre-calculated answers.

They tell us the probability of the event when x is less then OR equal
to our x.

The special notation we use for Poisson is X \~ Po(λ)

Which means the random variable X is distributed by the Poisson
distribution with a mean of lambda.

:notable:
Sometimes the numbbers come out too large for the Poisson
formula to handle it
(exponential growth), so we need to use approximation to
the Normal
Distribution. (Usually > 15 but the calculator would handle numbers up to 25...)

To do that you need to do a *Continuity Correction* for the Possion
Distribution.

When translating discrete data from continuous data we need to make sure that
we 'cover' all the discrete data values.

We need to make sure that when X \~ Po(15) and the question asks for P(X >= 14),
then during translation add a 0.5 to make sure the value 14 is covered.

after translation this would be -> X \~ No(15, sqrt(15))
*λ becomes µ*

Even though normal distribution normally takes 2 parameters, both are filled
by lambda and the square root of lambda respectively (lambda is the mean
in Poisson Distribution).

This is thanks to the poisson's property of having a variance equal to it's
mean.

Effectively we end up with X \~ Po(λ) -> X \~ No(λ, λ) (ish)

When using the 'z formula' 

`z = x - (λ) / (sqrt(λ))`

Then look at the tables.

    >> DISTRIBUTION 

Similarly, the normal (Gaussian) Distribution also uses this notation.

`X \~ N(µ, σ^2)`

The function takes 2 parameters - mean and variance (NOT sd),

Coincidentally, when the mean in Poisson's distributed approaches 15,
it be.g.ins to look (on a graph) exactly like the normal distribution.

We can use integration to find the probability of a certain variable
being x, although it is much easier to convert or standardise, and create
a graph such that `Z \~ N(0, 1)`

:length: short 
:type: paragraph

Which means that random variable Z is distributed by Normal Distribution
with a mean (MU) of 0 (which causes the graph to be split by the y axis
on the Cartesian plane) and variance of 1, which causes the standard
deviation to be also 1.

`z = (x - µ) / σ`

Using the tables we can also find the score, but they, just like with
Poisson, will be shown as probability of random variable being ... OR
lower.

This `z` formula allow us to transform every Gaussian distribution into a curve
in this standardised form. As a result we can use tables.

