    >>>> VARIABLES

Adding or subtracting a *fixed value c (a constant)* should shift the expected value
by the same amount (along with the mean), 
but *leave the variance unchanged (and sd)* (the center of the distribution of data
produced by sampling X would shift by the amount c but its *spread would be unaffected*): 

Spread is uneffected if we add to all values in our distribution.

a) soem

If we add to our dataset a constant, then the mean after this will go up by
that constant ie`new_mean = old_mean + constant`

`E(X ± c) = E(X) ± c`

`Var(X ± c) = Var(X)`

The mean of the sum of two random variables X and Y is the sum of their means.
`µ(X + Y) = µ(X) + µ(Y)`

When you either add or subtract the standard deviation needs to be converted
to variance, then you add the variances of your random variables (even in
the case of subtraction) and take the square root of that.
 
`Var(a*X) = a^2 * Var(X)`

Addition and subtraction of the mean is simple - just multiply and add or
take away.

    >>> MEAN 

Normally`mean = sum of all data points / number of data points`

However, when we have the mean, and the number of items of 2 data sets and want
to get the combined mean, we need:

# the overall number of items in our new dataset i.e.

    `len(DataSet1) + len(DataSet2)`

# the total sum of all data points from both datasets i.e.

    `average(DataSet1) * len(DataSet1) + avergage(DataSet2) * len(DataSet2)`

now we have to combined total scores for both datasets
and combined length of both datasets.

Use the regular mean formula:
`mean = sum of all data points / number of data points`

